{
  "texts": [
    "Our frequency result added new empirical evidence to the research showing that difficulty and learnability are closely associated (Eckman, 1977).",
    "Further, we find that with learners' levels of proficiency advances, they produce complex degree expressions more frequently.",
    "We also find evidence that higher surprisals are associated with lower proficiency in degree expressions usage, the use of surprisals proves to be more effective than using the existing measures of cohesion in predicting proficiency of degree expressions usage, and that LLMs-surprisals capture distinct L2 degree expressions development features.",
    "These surprisals-related findings extended and added to the research by Kharkwal and Muresan (2014) and Cong (2024).",
    "Overall, our results indicate that LLMs and NLP are promising tools in improving our understanding of L2 development in degree expressions."
  ]
}